Restart policies.

By default, a container that exits stays exited. But production services need to recover from crashes and from host reboots, and that is what the restart flag controls.

There are four policies. No, the default, means never restart. On-failure, with an optional retry count, restarts only if the container exits with a non-zero code. Always restarts the container whenever it exits and whenever the daemon starts, so it comes back after a daemon restart or a host reboot, and notably it comes back even if you stopped it manually. And unless-stopped behaves like always, except that if you explicitly stop it, it stays stopped across daemon restarts. That last one is the usual production choice, and a typical production line runs a container detached with the restart policy set to unless-stopped and a clear name.

A few details bite people. The restart policy only applies after the first successful start, so a container that fails to start at all, because of a bad image or a syntax error, does not get retried. The restart backoff is exponential and capped at about a minute, so a crash-looping container does not hammer the host. The restart counter resets once the container has run successfully for ten seconds. The restart flag and the remove-on-exit flag are mutually exclusive, so you pick one. And you can inspect a container to read back both its policy and how many times it has actually restarted.
